&gt; First define disability. 
&gt; IMO, before you can define Accessibility you must first define disability. 
OK. 
Here's my short definition: 
&quot;Disability is a design flaw in the environment.&quot; 
Here's the long version, from a chapter in an upcoming book on webbased training: 
&quot;People are not &quot;disabled.&quot; 
A disability is a consequence of design flaws in the environment. 
Some individuals, due to accident, illness, or heredity, have difficulties performing  or cannot perform  certain tasks, such as moving their legs, seeing, hearing, talking, grasping or lifting. 
When these functional limitations are severe enough to adversely affect a person's performance, and the natural and human environments fail to accommodate their functional limitations, the individual is said to have a disability.&quot; 
You take your pick. 
If I were rewriting it, I would say something like this: 
... ALL individuals, due to circumstance, accident, illness, or heredity, have difficulties performing  or cannot perform  certain tasks... 
